## Description {#details}

This file supports working with JSON data.

It comprises:


<ul>
<li>classes which hold dynamically-typed parsed JSON structures These are value types that can be composed, inspected, and modified. See json::Value, and the related types json::Object and json::Array.</li>
<li>functions to parse JSON text into Values, and to serialize Values to text. See <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/linetable-cpp/#a45e99fb329714d8911cb5e116eb8a3bc">parse()</a>, operator&lt;&lt;, and format&#95;provider.</li>
<li>a convention and helpers for mapping between json::Value and user-defined types. See fromJSON(), ObjectMapper, and the class comment on Value.</li>
<li>an output API json::OStream which can emit JSON without materializing all structures as json::Value.</li>
</ul>


Typically, JSON data would be read from an external source, parsed into a Value, and then converted into some native data structure before doing real work on it. (And vice versa when writing).

Other serialization mechanisms you may consider:


<ul>
<li>YAML is also text-based, and more human-readable than JSON. It&#39;s a more complex format and data model, and YAML parsers aren&#39;t ubiquitous. <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/support/yamlparser-h">YAMLParser.h</a> is a streaming parser suitable for parsing large documents (including JSON, as YAML is a superset). It can be awkward to use directly. YAML I/O (<a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/support/yamltraits-h">YAMLTraits.h</a>) provides data mapping that is more declarative than the toJSON/fromJSON conventions here.</li>
<li>LLVM bitstream is a space- and CPU- efficient binary format. Typically it encodes LLVM IR (&quot;bitcode&quot;), but it can be a container for other data. Low-level reader/writer libraries are in Bitstream/Bitstream&#42;.h</li>
</ul>

<Link id="l00210" /><CodeLine lineNumber="210"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00211" /><CodeLine lineNumber="211"><Highlight kind="comment">/// A Value is an JSON value of unknown type.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00212" /><CodeLine lineNumber="212"><Highlight kind="comment">/// They can be copied, but should generally be moved.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00213" /><CodeLine lineNumber="213"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00214" /><CodeLine lineNumber="214"><Highlight kind="comment">/// === Composing values ===</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00215" /><CodeLine lineNumber="215"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00216" /><CodeLine lineNumber="216"><Highlight kind="comment">/// You can implicitly construct Values from:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00217" /><CodeLine lineNumber="217"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - strings: std::string, SmallString, formatv, StringRef, char&#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00218" /><CodeLine lineNumber="218"><Highlight kind="comment">///              (char&#42;, and StringRef are references, not copies!)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00219" /><CodeLine lineNumber="219"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - numbers</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00220" /><CodeLine lineNumber="220"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - booleans</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00221" /><CodeLine lineNumber="221"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - null: nullptr</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00222" /><CodeLine lineNumber="222"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - arrays: &#123;&quot;foo&quot;, 42.0, false&#125;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00223" /><CodeLine lineNumber="223"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - serializable things: types with toJSON(const T&amp;)-&gt;Value, found by ADL</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00224" /><CodeLine lineNumber="224"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00225" /><CodeLine lineNumber="225"><Highlight kind="comment">/// They can also be constructed from object/array helpers:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00226" /><CodeLine lineNumber="226"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - json::Object is a type like map&lt;ObjectKey, Value&gt;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00227" /><CodeLine lineNumber="227"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - json::Array is a type like vector&lt;Value&gt;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00228" /><CodeLine lineNumber="228"><Highlight kind="comment">/// These can be list-initialized, or used to build up collections in a loop.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00229" /><CodeLine lineNumber="229"><Highlight kind="comment">/// json::ary(Collection) converts all items in a collection to Values.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00230" /><CodeLine lineNumber="230"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00231" /><CodeLine lineNumber="231"><Highlight kind="comment">/// === Inspecting values ===</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00232" /><CodeLine lineNumber="232"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00233" /><CodeLine lineNumber="233"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Each Value is one of the JSON kinds:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00234" /><CodeLine lineNumber="234"><Highlight kind="comment">///   null    (nullptr&#95;t)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00235" /><CodeLine lineNumber="235"><Highlight kind="comment">///   boolean (bool)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00236" /><CodeLine lineNumber="236"><Highlight kind="comment">///   number  (double, int64 or uint64)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00237" /><CodeLine lineNumber="237"><Highlight kind="comment">///   string  (StringRef)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00238" /><CodeLine lineNumber="238"><Highlight kind="comment">///   array   (json::Array)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00239" /><CodeLine lineNumber="239"><Highlight kind="comment">///   object  (json::Object)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00240" /><CodeLine lineNumber="240"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00241" /><CodeLine lineNumber="241"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The kind can be queried directly, or implicitly via the typed accessors:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00242" /><CodeLine lineNumber="242"><Highlight kind="comment">///   if (std::optional&lt;StringRef&gt; S = E.getAsString()</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00243" /><CodeLine lineNumber="243"><Highlight kind="comment">///     assert(E.kind() == Value::String);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00244" /><CodeLine lineNumber="244"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00245" /><CodeLine lineNumber="245"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Array and Object also have typed indexing accessors for easy traversal:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00246" /><CodeLine lineNumber="246"><Highlight kind="comment">///   Expected&lt;Value&gt; E = parse(R&quot;( &#123;&quot;options&quot;: &#123;&quot;font&quot;: &quot;sans-serif&quot;&#125;&#125; )&quot;);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00247" /><CodeLine lineNumber="247"><Highlight kind="comment">///   if (Object&#42; O = E-&gt;getAsObject())</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00248" /><CodeLine lineNumber="248"><Highlight kind="comment">///     if (Object&#42; Opts = O-&gt;getObject(&quot;options&quot;))</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00249" /><CodeLine lineNumber="249"><Highlight kind="comment">///       if (std::optional&lt;StringRef&gt; Font = Opts-&gt;getString(&quot;font&quot;))</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00250" /><CodeLine lineNumber="250"><Highlight kind="comment">///         assert(Opts-&gt;at(&quot;font&quot;).kind() == Value::String);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00251" /><CodeLine lineNumber="251"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00252" /><CodeLine lineNumber="252"><Highlight kind="comment">/// === Converting JSON values to C++ types ===</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00253" /><CodeLine lineNumber="253"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00254" /><CodeLine lineNumber="254"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The convention is to have a deserializer function findable via ADL:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00255" /><CodeLine lineNumber="255"><Highlight kind="comment">///     fromJSON(const json::Value&amp;, T&amp;, Path) -&gt; bool</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00256" /><CodeLine lineNumber="256"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00257" /><CodeLine lineNumber="257"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The return value indicates overall success, and Path is used for precise</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00258" /><CodeLine lineNumber="258"><Highlight kind="comment">/// error reporting. (The Path::Root passed in at the top level fromJSON call</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00259" /><CodeLine lineNumber="259"><Highlight kind="comment">/// captures any nested error and can render it in context).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00260" /><CodeLine lineNumber="260"><Highlight kind="comment">/// If conversion fails, fromJSON calls Path::report() and immediately returns.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00261" /><CodeLine lineNumber="261"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This ensures that the first fatal error survives.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00262" /><CodeLine lineNumber="262"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00263" /><CodeLine lineNumber="263"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Deserializers are provided for:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00264" /><CodeLine lineNumber="264"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - bool</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00265" /><CodeLine lineNumber="265"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - int and int64&#95;t</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00266" /><CodeLine lineNumber="266"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - double</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00267" /><CodeLine lineNumber="267"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - std::string</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00268" /><CodeLine lineNumber="268"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - vector&lt;T&gt;, where T is deserializable</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00269" /><CodeLine lineNumber="269"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - map&lt;string, T&gt;, where T is deserializable</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00270" /><CodeLine lineNumber="270"><Highlight kind="comment">///   - std::optional&lt;T&gt;, where T is deserializable</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00271" /><CodeLine lineNumber="271"><Highlight kind="comment">/// ObjectMapper can help writing fromJSON() functions for object types.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00272" /><CodeLine lineNumber="272"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00273" /><CodeLine lineNumber="273"><Highlight kind="comment">/// For conversion in the other direction, the serializer function is:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00274" /><CodeLine lineNumber="274"><Highlight kind="comment">///    toJSON(const T&amp;) -&gt; json::Value</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00275" /><CodeLine lineNumber="275"><Highlight kind="comment">/// If this exists, then it also allows constructing Value from T, and can</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00276" /><CodeLine lineNumber="276"><Highlight kind="comment">/// be used to serialize vector&lt;T&gt;, map&lt;string, T&gt;, and std::optional&lt;T&gt;.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00277" /><CodeLine lineNumber="277"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00278" /><CodeLine lineNumber="278"><Highlight kind="comment">/// === Serialization ===</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00279" /><CodeLine lineNumber="279"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00280" /><CodeLine lineNumber="280"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Values can be serialized to JSON:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00281" /><CodeLine lineNumber="281"><Highlight kind="comment">///   1) raw&#95;ostream &lt;&lt; Value                    // Basic formatting.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00282" /><CodeLine lineNumber="282"><Highlight kind="comment">///   2) raw&#95;ostream &lt;&lt; formatv(&quot;&#123;0&#125;&quot;, Value)    // Basic formatting.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00283" /><CodeLine lineNumber="283"><Highlight kind="comment">///   3) raw&#95;ostream &lt;&lt; formatv(&quot;&#123;0:2&#125;&quot;, Value)  // Pretty-print with indent 2</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00284" /><CodeLine lineNumber="284"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00285" /><CodeLine lineNumber="285"><Highlight kind="comment">/// And parsed:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00286" /><CodeLine lineNumber="286"><Highlight kind="comment">///   Expected&lt;Value&gt; E = json::parse(&quot;&#91;1, 2, null&#93;&quot;);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00287" /><CodeLine lineNumber="287"><Highlight kind="comment">///   assert(E &amp;&amp; E-&gt;kind() == Value::Array);</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00487" /><CodeLine lineNumber="487"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Unpoisoning to prevent overwriting poisoned object (e.g., annotated short</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00488" /><CodeLine lineNumber="488"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// string). Objects that have had their memory poisoned may cause an ASan</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00489" /><CodeLine lineNumber="489"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// error if their memory is reused without calling their destructor.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00490" /><CodeLine lineNumber="490"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Unpoisoning the memory prevents this error from occurring.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00491" /><CodeLine lineNumber="491"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// FIXME: This is a temporary solution to prevent buildbots from failing.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00492" /><CodeLine lineNumber="492"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//  The more appropriate approach would be to call the object&#39;s destructor</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00493" /><CodeLine lineNumber="493"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//  to unpoison memory. This would prevent any potential memory leaks (long</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00494" /><CodeLine lineNumber="494"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//  strings). Read for details:</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00495" /><CodeLine lineNumber="495"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//  https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/pull/79065#discussion&#95;r1462621761</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00496" /><CodeLine lineNumber="496"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/support/compiler-h/#a820fe7b3006fe7b31f19b0258993606a">&#95;&#95;asan&#95;unpoison&#95;memory&#95;region</a>(&amp;Union, </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">sizeof</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">(<a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/target/lib/target/mips/mips16isellowering-cpp/#a0acb682b8260ab1c60b918599864e2e5">T</a>));</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00924" /><CodeLine lineNumber="924"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00925" /><CodeLine lineNumber="925"><Highlight kind="comment">/// json::OStream allows writing well-formed JSON without materializing</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00926" /><CodeLine lineNumber="926"><Highlight kind="comment">/// all structures as json::Value ahead of time.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00927" /><CodeLine lineNumber="927"><Highlight kind="comment">/// It&#39;s faster, lower-level, and less safe than OS &lt;&lt; json::Value.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00928" /><CodeLine lineNumber="928"><Highlight kind="comment">/// It also allows emitting more constructs, such as comments.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00929" /><CodeLine lineNumber="929"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00930" /><CodeLine lineNumber="930"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Only one &quot;top-level&quot; object can be written to a stream.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00931" /><CodeLine lineNumber="931"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Simplest usage involves passing lambdas (Blocks) to fill in containers:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00932" /><CodeLine lineNumber="932"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00933" /><CodeLine lineNumber="933"><Highlight kind="comment">///   json::OStream J(OS);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00934" /><CodeLine lineNumber="934"><Highlight kind="comment">///   J.array(&#91;&amp;&#93;&#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00935" /><CodeLine lineNumber="935"><Highlight kind="comment">///     for (const Event &amp;E : Events)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00936" /><CodeLine lineNumber="936"><Highlight kind="comment">///       J.object(&#91;&amp;&#93; &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00937" /><CodeLine lineNumber="937"><Highlight kind="comment">///         J.attribute(&quot;timestamp&quot;, int64&#95;t(E.Time));</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00938" /><CodeLine lineNumber="938"><Highlight kind="comment">///         J.attributeArray(&quot;participants&quot;, &#91;&amp;&#93; &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00939" /><CodeLine lineNumber="939"><Highlight kind="comment">///           for (const Participant &amp;P : E.Participants)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00940" /><CodeLine lineNumber="940"><Highlight kind="comment">///             J.value(P.toString());</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00941" /><CodeLine lineNumber="941"><Highlight kind="comment">///         &#125;);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00942" /><CodeLine lineNumber="942"><Highlight kind="comment">///       &#125;);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00943" /><CodeLine lineNumber="943"><Highlight kind="comment">///   &#125;);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00944" /><CodeLine lineNumber="944"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00945" /><CodeLine lineNumber="945"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This would produce JSON like:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00946" /><CodeLine lineNumber="946"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00947" /><CodeLine lineNumber="947"><Highlight kind="comment">///   &#91;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00948" /><CodeLine lineNumber="948"><Highlight kind="comment">///     &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00949" /><CodeLine lineNumber="949"><Highlight kind="comment">///       &quot;timestamp&quot;: 19287398741,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00950" /><CodeLine lineNumber="950"><Highlight kind="comment">///       &quot;participants&quot;: &#91;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00951" /><CodeLine lineNumber="951"><Highlight kind="comment">///         &quot;King Kong&quot;,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00952" /><CodeLine lineNumber="952"><Highlight kind="comment">///         &quot;Miley Cyrus&quot;,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00953" /><CodeLine lineNumber="953"><Highlight kind="comment">///         &quot;Cleopatra&quot;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00954" /><CodeLine lineNumber="954"><Highlight kind="comment">///       &#93;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00955" /><CodeLine lineNumber="955"><Highlight kind="comment">///     &#125;,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00956" /><CodeLine lineNumber="956"><Highlight kind="comment">///     ...</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00957" /><CodeLine lineNumber="957"><Highlight kind="comment">///   &#93;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00958" /><CodeLine lineNumber="958"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00959" /><CodeLine lineNumber="959"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The lower level begin/end methods (arrayBegin()) are more flexible but</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00960" /><CodeLine lineNumber="960"><Highlight kind="comment">/// care must be taken to pair them correctly:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00961" /><CodeLine lineNumber="961"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00962" /><CodeLine lineNumber="962"><Highlight kind="comment">///   json::OStream J(OS);</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00963" /><CodeLine lineNumber="963"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//    J.arrayBegin();</Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00964" /><CodeLine lineNumber="964"><Highlight kind="comment">///   for (const Event &amp;E : Events) &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00965" /><CodeLine lineNumber="965"><Highlight kind="comment">///     J.objectBegin();</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00966" /><CodeLine lineNumber="966"><Highlight kind="comment">///     J.attribute(&quot;timestamp&quot;, int64&#95;t(E.Time));</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00967" /><CodeLine lineNumber="967"><Highlight kind="comment">///     J.attributeBegin(&quot;participants&quot;);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00968" /><CodeLine lineNumber="968"><Highlight kind="comment">///     for (const Participant &amp;P : E.Participants)</Highlight></CodeLine>
